title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a field. A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Jordan algebra</html:dfn> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is a nonassociative algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> whose multiplication satisfies:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>commutative: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[xy=yx]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Jordan identity: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(xy)(xx)=x(y(xx))]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>Note that Springer and Veldkamp's <fr:link
type="local"
href="veldkamp-2000-octonions.xml"
addr="veldkamp-2000-octonions"
title="Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups">Octonions, Jordan Algebras, and Exceptional Groups</fr:link> (remark 5.1.7, pg 122) note that the character of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {char}(J)\neq  2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
