title="The Octonions">[baez-2002-octonions]</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>There are four infinite families of formally real Jordan algebras and one exception:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>The algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(n,\mathbb {R})]]></fr:tex> with the Jordan product</fr:li>
<fr:li>The algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(n,\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex> with the Jordan product</fr:li>
<fr:li>The algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(n,\mathbb {H})]]></fr:tex> with the Jordan product</fr:li>
<fr:li>The <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Spin Factor</html:dfn> algebra <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^{n}\oplus \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> with the product <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(v,\alpha )\circ (w,\beta )=(\alpha  w+\beta  v, \langle  v,w\rangle  + \alpha \beta )]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Exceptional Jordan algebra</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {H}(3,\mathbb {O})]]></fr:tex> with the Jordan product</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>(See section 3 of John Baez's <fr:link
